<TITLE> 213 confirmed H1N1 cases up to Monday morning </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Aug 31 (bdnews24.com)The Institute of Epidemiology, Disease Control and Research (IEDCR) confirmed 14 new cases on Monday morning, taking the government's tally of recorded swine flu cases to 213. IEDCR has also confirmed the first H1N1 fatality in Bangladesh. Doctors at Lab Aid Hospital in Dhaka said the victim was a 35-year old woman. "A swine flu positive patient died last night at a private hospital in the capital," IEDCR director Mahmudur Rahman told bdnews24.com on Monday. Rahman said the patient had been suffering severe symptoms and complications related to swine flu. "This is the first recorded swine flu death in Bangladesh," he said. A senior doctor at Lab Aid Hospital in Dhanmondi told bdnews24.com that Mitali Chakravarty, 35, a swine flu patient in critical condition, had died at around 10.30pm on Sunday night. Mitali, of Savar's Uttar Para, was one IEDCR's confirmed H1N1 cases, Dr Samiran Kumar Saha, professor of medicine at Lab Aid and the patient's supervising doctor, told bdnews24.com on the night. She was admitted to Savar's Enam Medical College Hospital on Aug 16 with suspected dengue, but when it was clear her symptoms did not match dengue, and might be swine flu, Mita was transferred to Lab Aid Hospital in Dhanmondi, her family said. "Mitali was admitted to Lab Aid Hospital on Aug 20, and subsequent tests of IEDCR confirmed she had contracted the H1N1, or swine flu, virus," said Saha. "Her condition was serious as she was suffering complications with pneumonia.
